{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_ilia_ver01/data/sn87055779/00416150849/1930071901/0510.xml":{"full_text":"r\n36\nPAGES\nTODAY\nSOUTH BEND NEWS-TIMES\nEdition\nSuburban\nvol xr vii no ?nn*\nSOUTH BEND. INDIANA. SATURDAY. TULY 19. 1930\nTWO PARTS\u2014PART ONE\nPRICE THREE CENTS\n'V'\ni\ni\nI BANDIT IS FOUND\nAT HOTEL DOOM\nAFTER GUN FIGHT\nRobbers Suddenly Draw\nGuns While Waiting\nfor Patrol Wagon.\nBy International News Service:\nCHICAGO, July 18.\u2014Harry Yetter\nFri lay confessed he shot and killed Po\nliceman John J. Guiltanane, 35, and\ncritically wounded his partner, An\nthon: P. Wistart. Yetter was arrested\nin the hotel room of his sweetheart.\nThe shooting took place a few hours\nearlier after the policemen collared\nYetter and an unidentified companion\nholding up a South Side garage. The\nbandits produced weapons which the\nfficers failed to find when they\n.arched them.\nBullet In Head\nlltanane was killed by a bul\nthrough the head. Wistart\nshot through the abdomen and\nis believed to be dying. Their pris\noners fled on foot.\nSquads of police rushed into the\nSouth Side when the shooting was re\nported. In the bandits' abandoned\ncar they found a license card issued\nto Andrew Vanosky. Vanosky said\nYetter had borrowed the machine and\nmight be found at the Parkland hotel.\nYetter was then arrested in the\nroom of Mrs. Marjorie Gossette, 35.\nThe hotel clerk said he had stumbled\ninto the place about 4 a. m.\nVanosky, Mrs. Gossette, and three\nmen found with Vanosky are also in\ncustody.\nGuiltanane and Wistart had been\nlooking for the two men in a small\nsedan, only one light of which was\nburning, who had held up an oil sta\ntion earlier today.\nVisit Sales Agency\nThe officers decided to Visit the\nMorgan Park Auto Sales agency in\nthe \u2018belief the bandits might have\ngone there to have their auto head\n1\n\n\u25a0\\y\nWhen the officers stepped into the\ngarage they discovered one of the\nbandits holding up Elisha Alford,\nNegro night porter. Surprised from\nbehind by the officers, the bandit\nsurrendered -without offering resist*\nence and his companion, who was\nwaiting outside, also surrendered im\nmediately.\nDraw Concealed Gun\nThe bandits handed over their\nguns as Policeman Fred Jergun, on\npatrol duty, walked past. Guiltarane\nand Wistart asked. Jergun to call a\npatrol wagon for them and stood with\ntheir prisoners awaiting Jergun\u2019s re\nturn.\nSuddenly, both bandits drew con\ncealed guns and fired upon the offi\ncers. Both policemen dropped in\nstantly. Jergun, a block away, heard\nthe shooting and ran back to the\ngarage, but the bandits had escaped,\nleaving their car at the curb.\nIn a side pocket of the auto, Jergun\nfound a license card made out to\nAndrew Vanosky and another card\nindicating Vanosky had recently been\nparoled for some offense.\nDRIVER IS INJURED\nAS TRUCK BURNS\nINDIANAPOLIS, July 18.\u2014Henry\nHicks, 22, of Chicago, was slightly in\njured and his truck and its cargo of\nmerchandise valued at $4,000 were\ndestroyed by fire, when Hicks crashed\ninto a tree a half mile north of\nFlackville on state road 52 today.\nHicks was enroute to Indianapolis\nwith a truck load of candy, syrups\nand other products consigned to the\nUniversal Car Loading Co., of this\ncity.\nThe injured truck driver was taken\nto the City hospital where his in\njuries were treated.\nTYPHOON DESTROYS\n400 KOREAN HOMES\nBy Flitted Trent:\nFUSAN, Korea, July 18.\u2014More\nthan 400 houses were destroyed and\ncrops in surrounding territory laid\nwaste by a typhoon which swept over\nFusan today.\nIt was reported that southern Korea\nwas devastated and that shipping was\nparalyzed.\nMany of the smaller craft were\nsunk by the heavy seas caused by the\ntyphoon and their crews were re\nported lost.\nWif'eamer\\\nV!\n\na.\nIndiana\u2014Mostly fair south, possibly\nshowers or thunderstorms north por\ntion Saturday; cooler.\nLower Michigan\u2014Mostly cloudy, lo\ncal showers or thunderstorms prob\nable Saturday; cooler south portion.\nLocal atmospheric conditions for the\nnext 24 hours as indicated by The\nXews-Timos baronvter:\nUnsettled weather with Increasing\nwinds.\nThe following temperatures were re\ncorded by The News-Times thermom\neter from 9 o'clock Thursday night\nto 9 o'clock Friday night;\n9 p. m....80\n10 p.m..78\n11'p. m.78\nMidnight.7ti\n1 a. ..70\n2 a. n>. .75\n3 a. m. ..74\n4 a. m.73\n5 a. m. .71\n8 a. m. ,,......73\n7 a. m.....81\n8 a. m.82\n9 a. m.84\n10 a. m.88\n11 a. m. ........92\n-Noon ..98\n1 p. m.\n2 p. m.\n.3 p. m.\n4 p. m.\n5 p. m.\nB p. i*.\n7 p. m.\n8 pm.\n9 p. m.\n.97\n.98\n.99\n.99\n.100\n.100\n..00\n.......98\n.95\nMagic Surgery\nMends Broken\nAnkle at Once\nBy United Preset\nCHICAGO, July 18. \u2014Magic of\nmodern surgery turned a broken leg\nInto a mere minor accident Friday\nat the Cook county hospital.\nA few minutes after the new treat\nment had been administered to a\nwoman with a badly fractured ankle,\nshe got up from the operting table\nand walked around, none the worse\nfor her experience.\nMore than 100 physicians witnessed\nthe demonstration, a clinic in a new\nmethod of treating fractures, devised\nand administered by Dr. Lorenz Boeh\nler, head of the Vienna Industrial\nhospital. Dr. Karl Meyer, Cook\ncounty hospital superintendent char\nacterized the treatment as one of the\npresent generation\u2019s major contribu\ntions to surgery.\nLocal Anaesthetic\n\"The key to the new method of\ntreating fractures is by using a local\ninstead of a general anaesthetic,\u201d ex\nplained Dr. Meyer. \u201cThe conventional\nmethod is to give the patient a gen\neral anaesthetic and put the arm or\nleg in a plaster cast. The patient\nmust stay in bed several days. By\nDr. Boehler\u2019s method a local ana\nsethetic of less than an ounce of 2\nper cent novocaine is injected after\nthe x-ray picture has been taken and\nthe fracture, charted.\n\u201cThen the limb is ptit in the cast\nand in a short time the patient is\nInvited to make use of it.\n\"Not only is time saved and suffer\ning eliminated, but Jt\u00bbw using the local\nanaesthetic the fWtcrure can be re\nduced two or three times if neces\nsary in order to get perfect results.\u201d\nMrs. Anna Veronica, office worker,\nwas the patient able to walk two\nhours after Dr. Boehler started to\nwork on her ankle. She smiled and\ntalked to him while he manipu\nlated his instruments and announced\nthat she expected to be at her desk\nas usual Saturday.\nDISCOVER WOMAN\nBEATEN TO DEATH\nBrother and Nephew Are\nSought in Murder;\nJewels Missing.\nBy United Preen\nSAUGUS, Mass., July 18.\u2014With her\nhead and face battered almost beyond\nrecognition, Mrs. Edith Thompsofl,\n51-year-old department store detec\ntive, was found murdered in the sun\nporch of her home here Thursday.\nHer body was discovered by Police\nChief Roland Mansfield, who was\nsummoned to her Vine street home\nafter being informed that winded* of\nthe Thompson apartment had been\nopen since Tuesday and that an auto\nmobile owned by the woman had been\nparked in the yard for several days.\nJewels Missing.\nImmediately after discovery of the\nbody, it was learned, a chamois bag,\nsaid to have contained jewelry valued\nat more than 810,000, which the wom\nan wore around her neck, was miss\ning. Police, however, refused to ad\nvance robbery as a motive for the\ncrime.\nState police, called into the case,\nannounced 'they were seeking for\nquestioning Nardy- Thompson, 26, a\nnephew, who, they claimed, was per\nhaps the last person to see Mrs.\nThompson alive.\nThe nephew, authorities said, was\nseen with Mrs. Thompson on Tues\nday, the day set by investigators as\nthe time of her death. Dr. George\nBurgess Magrath, medical examiner,\nplaced the time of the murder as\n10:30 Tuesday morning.\nUnwashed breakfast dishes and un\ncalled for newspapers, police said,\naided them in establishing, tentative\nly, the time of the murder.\nSeek Brother.\nA brother, William Thompson, who\ninvestigators said lived at his sister\u2019s\nhome until recently, was also being\nsought for questioning.\nThe Jewelry, which Mrs. Thompson\nwas said to have had in her posses\nsion, was bequeathed her several years\nago by a Boston police inspector. For\nmany years, Mrs. Thompson was em\nployed as a detective in various Bos\nton department stores, recently being\nengaged in that work at Lynn.\nBRITISH LABORFTES\nTear mace seizure\nBy International J>aw\u00bb-SrrTlce:\nLONDON, July 18.\u2014Dire political\nconsequences were, feared by left\nwing labor members today as the\naftermath of John Beckett\u2019s sensa\ntional seizure in the house of com\nmons of the golden mace\u2014symbol of\nparliamentary authority\u2014from' the\ntable before the speaker's chair and\nhoisting It across his shoulder in pro\ntest to being refused a hearing on his\nviews on India.\nIt precipitated the worst scene in\nparliament in 300 years. Only one\nother time had the sacred emblem\nbeen touched rudely since the his\ntorical occasion when Oliver Crom\nwell blustered into the chamber and\npointing to the mace, disdainfully\ncried to his followers: \u201cTake away\nthat bauble!\u201d\nBeckett, member for Camberwell,\nwas peremptorarlly seized after tak\ning hardly five steps with the golden\nmace in his arms and ordered out of\nthe chamber.\nSOLE PASSENGER\nAND CREW SAVED\nBY BRITISH SHIP\nFrantic SOS Calls of\nBlazing Ship Brings\nAid in Time.\nBy International News-Service:\nLONDON, July 18.\u2014In a dramatic\nmid-ocean rescue, the sole passenger\nand 42 members of the crew of the\nNorth German Lloyd freighter Targis\nwere saved from death by a British\nsteamer today when the Targis burned\nand sank 800 miles east of Bermuda.\nThe Targis, a steel vessel of 5,952\ntons, ordinarily carries between 14\nand 18 passengers as supercargo. At\nthe offices of the North German Lloyd\nline here, however, it was said that\nonly one passenger was aboard in ad\ndition to the crew.\nThe rescue was effected by the\nBritish freighter Rangitoto, registered\nat Auckland, N. Z.\nMessages Tell Rescue\nNews of the rescue was contained\nin brief wireless messages from the\nmaster of the Rangitoto, which ans\nwered the Targis\u2019 call for help late\nlast night. The Rangitoto, a freighter\nof 985 tons gross, found the Targis\nablaze, with fire burning fiercely in\nthree of her holds.\nSmall boats were put out from the\nRangitoto, and the single passenger\ntaken aboard the rescue ship. The\ncrew remained aboard the burning\nliner in an effort to extinguish the\nflames.\nWhen the blaze became hopelessly\nout of control, the captain of the Tar\ngis abandoned efforts to save his ship;\nand the crew took to the boats. They\nwere taken aboard the Rangitoto\nwhich continued to stand by until the\nTargis slipped beneath the waves.\nReports Vessel Sunk\nThe captain of the Rangitoto then\nreported to his head offices that the\nTargis had sunk, that the passenger\nand crew had been rescued safely,\nand that he was proceeding to Southh\nampton immediately. The vessel is\ndue at that port on July 24.\nThe terse and characteristic wire\nless reports from the master of the\nRangitoto failed to reveal the cause\nj of the Targis\u2019 blaze. Both ships were\nequipped with wireless, but news of\nthe Targis\u2019 difficulty was not received\nuntil hours after the fire had broken\nI rmt\nWhile the freighter caught Are in a\nbusy steamer lane, the Rangitoto ap\nparently was the only vessel suffi\nciently near to respond to her frantic\nappeals for assistance.\nDue on July 27\nThe Targis, which plies with freight\nbetween the United States and Ger\nmany, was Journeying eastward when\nthe fire broke out. She was due at\nher home port of Bremen on July 27.\nThe identity of the Targis\u2019 single\npassenger was not known here. First\nreports said that between 14 and 18\npersons over and above the crew were\naboard the vessel, and it was reported\nthat one of them was an American.\nEfforts to confirm this report *were\nfutile.\nfrom the captain\u2019s messages, it ap\npeared no difficulty was encountered\nin launching lifeboats and rescuing\nthe crew.\nWeather Aids Rescue\nThe successful rescue work was\nmade possible, it is believed, by the\nfact calm weather prevailed at the\ntime of the disaster. The blaze from\nthe Targis\u2019 hold, illuminating the\nocean in a wide red swath of light\nmade easier the task of rescue\nworkers.\nNo estimate was obtainable here of\nthe financial loss sustained in the\nsinking of the Targis and destruction\nof her cargo.\nFREIGHTER SURVIVES\nICEBERG COLLISION\nBy International News-Services\nLONDON, July 18.\u2014The British\nfreighter Dalryan was refloated today\nafter collision with an iceberg in mid\nAtlantic, according to wireless mes\nsages to the United Steam Naviga\ntion Co., operators of the vessel. Ex\ntent of the damage done when the\nship stuck fast on a ledge of the berg\nwas not ascertained.\nSAYS PROSPERITY\nTO ELECT HOOVER\nSenator Copeland Advo\ncates Six-Hour Day,\nFive-Day Week.\nBy rnlt\u00abd Fmi:\nNEW YORK, July 18.\u2014President\nHoover will be re-e lee ted in 1932\nwith the return of prosperity to the\nUnited States, Senator Royal S.\nCopeland, of New York, said in an\naddress before the business stability\nconference of the garment trades\nhere Thursday night.\nConfining his talk mainly to the\neconomic trend of the country, Sen\nator Copeland advocated the six\nhour day and flve-day week, con\ndemned speculation, chain stores and\nbranch banks and then predicted the\nre-election f President Hoover with\nthe return of prosperity in 1932.\nHe said that America is not suffer\ning from depression any worse than\nare European countries, but the\nUnited States, he declared, is \u201ca*\nnear the economic bottom as a coun\ntry can go\". L\nPlenty High\ni don't knoiu^c\nwhether awbodv\nvjlia E\\JER hame\nA LADDER TALL\nENOUGH TO REACH\nTHAT!\nTHREE MEN PAY\nDEATH PENALTY\nGunmen Go to Electric\nChair with Protestations\nof Innocence.\nBy United Press:\nOSSINING, N. Y., July 18.\u2014Thre<\nBuffalo gunmen paid the state\u2019s pen\nalty for murder last night and diec\nwithin 20 minutes of each other ir\nthe electric chair at Sing Sing prison\nThe men were Alexander Bogde\nnoff, Max Rybarczyk, and Stepher\nGrezchowiak. They were convicted o'\nkilling Ferdinand Fechter, restauranl\nproprietor, during a holdup.\nBogdenoff\u2019s attempt to assume al\nthe blame failed to result in reprieve;\nfor the others but Rybarczyk anc\nGrezchowiak maintained their inno\ncence to the last.\nSmokes To Last\nGrezchowiak, a World war veteran\nwas smoking a cigaret as he enterec\nthe death chamber. He asked Warder\nLewis E. Lawes permission to flnist\nthe cigaret, and inhaled one deei\npuff. Then he sat down in the chair.\n\u201cTake a good look, gentlemen,\" h<\nsaid. \u201cYou are seeing an innocen\nman die.\u201d\nThe straps were adjusted and Exe\ncutioner Robert Elliott turned on tin\ncurrent. At 11:06 Grezchowiak wsu\npronounced dead.\nRybarczyk also met death witl\nfirmness and with protestations o:\ninnocence.\nHe strode beside the chair and said\n\u201cI\u2019m an innocent man. I\u2019m going t<\nleave you in a few minutes.\"\nHe was dead at 11:13.\nHe Doesn\u2019t Care\nThen came Bogdenoff, walkinj\nslowly as if to utilize what little tlm<\nwas left him in life. He too had t\nsDeech.\n\"Gentlemen, you are representative!\nof the state of New York. You hav<\njust seen them kill two innocent men\nI have tried previously to save then\nbut my words were no good.\u201d\nHe walked to the chair, tumec\nagain, and said:\n\"Well, why pray now? I don\u2019t giv<\na damn.\u201d\nBut the whispered words of th\u00ab\nRev. John P. McCoffrey could b<\nheard as Bogdenoff met death.\n5 INJURED BY AUTO\nCRASH AT CORNEB\nTERRE HAUTE, Ind., July 18.\nOne girl was injured, probably fatally\nand four other persons, including t\ntwo-year-old baby, received lessei\ninjuries, when two automobiles crash\ned at a street intersection here.\nLittle hope was hel* by hospita:\nattaches for the recovery of Mis!\nStelle Suewzey, 17, who received cut:\nand bruises and was badly burned ii\nthe crash. Mrs. Anna Ray, driver o:\none of the cars, Mrs. Marie Noyes\nEvelyn Wolfe, 13, and Jack Allen, 2\nwere released after being treated a\nthe hospital for their injuries.\nCharles Garrigus, 27, Cates, Ind.\ndriver of the second car, was onlj\nslightly bruised. s\nBoth cars overturned and were al\nmost completely wrecked.\n\n\nEDITOR NEWS-TIMES:\nSANTA MONICA, Calif., July 18.\n\u2014Humor is still rampant In the\nSenate. Here is the two latest\namendments to the treaty:\n\u201cFreedom of the seas for all neu\ntrals.\u201d That was originally sug\ngested at the same time that other\nfamous amendment was \u201cIf your\nenemy strike you turn the other\ncheek.\u201d\nWars are won by starvation. How\nyou going to starve anybody if\neverybody else feeds \u2019em?\nThe other gem of forlorn hope\nwas, \u201cEngland must give up five of\nher naval bases.\u201d\nI don\u2019t know how Senator Mc\nRellar overlooked Buckingham Pal\nace in that demand.\nYours,\nBRITAIN OPPOSES\nU.S. OF EOROPE\ni\nNote on Briand Appeal\nWarns Against Stopping\nLeague of Nations.\nPARIS, July 18.\u2014The British reply\nto the Briand plan for a United\nEurope, made public Thursday night\nexpressed frank doubt of the ad\nvisibility of organizing a European\nfederation.\nThe response, while studiously\ncourteous, delicately suggested that\nthe creation of a rival body might\ngive the impression the League of\nNations had been found inadequate\nand incompetent.\nThe six-page typewritten reply was\nreplete with phrases such as: \u2018\u2018if the\nBritish government thoroughly un\nderstands the propositions contained\nin the memorandum,\u201d and \u201cHis\nMajesty\u2019s government understands\nfrom the memorandum.\"\nWhile admitting the necessity for a\nbetter understanding among all Euro\npean nations and agreeing that the\neconomic phase of such an organiza\ntion was the most important Lodnon\ni replied that Britain was \u201cunconvinced\nthat a profound examination would\nreveal the necessity or desirability of\nthe establishment of new and inde\npendent international institutions.\u201d\nThe reply, which had been awaited\neagerly, particularly warned against\nthe danger of stifling the league and\nengendering bitterness on other con\ntinents.\nAn entire page was devoted to citing\nthe record of the League of Nations,\nparticularly its activities in connec\ntion with the Warsaw sanitary con\nference in 1922, and with regard to\nthe reconstruction of Austria and\nHungary.\nu\nW 4\nOGDEN TO PROBE\nGASOLINE FRAUDS\nLawyers for Alleged\n\u201cBootleg\u201d Companies\nConfer with Officials.\nBy International News-Service:\nINDIANAPOLIS, Ind., July 18.\u2014At\ntorney General James M. Ogden to\nday expected to meet attorneys for\nalleged \u201cbootleg\u201d gasoline companies\noperating in the Calumet district in\nan attempt to reach a settlement and\nto investigate allegations that a state\nemploye made a private collection in\nregard to the case. The lawyers were\nfrom Hammond.\nThe situation in the gasoline cases\nin which the state is alleged to have\nbeen defrauded of thousands of dol\nlars in unpaid gasoline taxes became\nacute with the resignation of State\nSenator Bruce E. Cooper, of Stewarts\nville, as auditor in the gasoline tax\ndepartment.\nLeland K. Fishback, department\nhead, revealed that Cooper had been\nsent to Lake county to investigate the\nreport that the state was being de\nfrauded last winter. Cooper returned\nwith the statement that the state was\ncollecting everything due to it, Fish\nback said. Only two months later,\nFishback said that he went to the\nCalumet district and discovered gaso\nline companies were cheating the\nstate of thousands of dollars.\nOIL INSPECTORS\nSHORT ON FUNDS\nBy International News-Service:\nINDIANAPOLIS, July 18.\u2014Close on\nthe heels of the \"bootleg\u201d gasoline\ntax sensation, another state house\nscandal burst forth Friday with the\nadmission that partial reports of the\nstate board of accounts disclose short\nages. in accounts of \"six or seven\"\nstate oil inspectors.\nThe alleged shortages total thou\nsands of dollars.\nThe reports, alleged to involve past\noil inspectors living at Greencastle,\nMarion and other cities, have been\nbefore Governor Harry G. Leslie for\nthe last four months, it was admitted\nby I. H. Miller, state food and drug\ninspector, and by an attache of the\ngovernor\u2019s office.\nLawrence F. Qrr, chief examiner of\nthe accounts board, also confirmed\nthe allegation that the reports have\ndisclosed alleged shortages in ac\ncounts.\nWithholds News\nGovernor Leslie had withheld in\nformation concerning the reports\npending an attempt to obtain settle\nment with the companies that issue\nbonds for the officials, it was said at\nhis office. The governor, who is at\nthe Dunes State park on vacation,\ncould not be reached.\nThe reports cover transactions of\nthe oil inspectors for many years\nback, it was learned, some of the dis\ncrepancies having occurred as long\nas seven or eight yean ago.\n\nJ\nShowers May\nBring Relief\nIn Heat Wave\nBjr I'nited Freag:\nCHICAGO, July 18.\u2014Chicago\u2019s mil\nlions sweltered Friday night in a heat\nwave which broke an all time record\nshortly before sundown when official\nthermometers touched 98.\nThe hottest July 18 here previously\nwas in 1912 when a temperature of 95\nwas recorded.\nA scorching sun beat down all day,\nmelting asphalt, collars and complex\nions. Dry winds veered in from the\nsouthwest, blistering paint, noses and\nautomobile tires. The combination ol\nsun and hot wind virtually wilted the\ncity\u2019s inhabitants.\nTheaters Jammed\nUsually busy streets were almost\nclear of pedestrians. The citizens\nsought instead the icy coolness of\nmovie theaters, which were jammed,\nand the slight relief afforded by the\nmiles of bathing beaches on Lake\nftflchigan. The beaches were packed\nfrom early morning until late at\nnight.\nRoads leading out of Chicago were\nfilled with automobiles, fender to\nfender creeping through the hot night\nto the somewhat lesser heat of nearby\nsummer resorts.\nPolice smiled and passed oh in the\ncity parks where thousands spent the\nnight on the turf. Tenement districts\n(Continued on page 4, column 4)\nI\nFIGHT ON SALARY\nIN MEGGER SGIT\nBethlehem\u2019s Head Con\ntends Bonus Has No\nBearing on Situation.\nBy BURL A. ELY\nInternational Neva Service Staff\nCorrespondent\nYOUNGSTOWN, O., July 18.\u2014Des\npite the admission that his annual\nsalary is a mere $12,000, the total\ncompensation of Eugene G. Grace as\npresident of Bethlehem Steel cor\nporation today was buried in the sec\nret of an \u201cunknown quantity\u201d of\nwhich the executive receives a bonus\nof one and one-half per cent.\nA virtual tug-of-war over Grace\u2019s\ncompensation as Bethlehem\u2019s chief\nwas staged in yesterday\u2019s common\npleas court hearing of the billion-dol\nlar lawsuit over the merger of\nYoungstown Sheet and Tube com\npany with Bethlehem, but the anti\nmerger attorneys struggled for the\nmost part in vain.\nGrace admitted that his compen\nsation was a salary of $12,000 plus a\nbonus of one and one-half per cent.\nHe pleaded ignorance, hawever, as to\nthe details of the bonus. He also con\nfessed ignorance as to what the bonus\nhad totaled for the months of April,\nMay and June\u2014the months Judge\nDavid G. Jenkins ruled he must ans\nwer questions concerning.\nAttorneys Argue\nGrace gave little testimony from\nthe witness stand yesterday, most\nof the time being consumed by argu\nments' between attorneys for and\nagainst the Sheet and Tube-Bethle-\nhem merger over the admissibility of\nGrace\u2019s compensation into the court\nrecords.\nAnti-merger attorneys contended\nthat Grace\u2019s compensation was the\nsubject of important allegations. They\nclaimed that stockholders of Sheet\nand Tube had not been informed of\nGrace\u2019s salary, and that a fraud had\nthereby been constituted.\nAttorneys for Grace argued that the\nquestion of Bethlehem\u2019s compensation\nto the executive involved \u201cmerely an\nunreasonable searching into the pro-\nfits of the plants of the defendant\ncorporation.\u201d\nJudge Jenkins finally ruled vthat\nGrace should answer questions dating\nback to April 30\u2014the earliest date on j\nwhich the Sheet and Tube Bethlehem\nmerger could have become eeffctive,\nthereby making the amount of Grace\u2019s\ncompensation since that time per-\ntinent to the issue.\nKOLB WEEPS ON\nWITNESS STAND\nMurder Defendant De\nnies He Killed Wives to\nGet Insurance.\nBy International >'ew\u00ab-f\u00bberrlee:\nGREENFIELD, Ind., July 18.\u2014\nState\u2019s attorneys today made a drive\nto shake testimony ol George Kolb,\n57, Rush county farmer and allleged\n\u201cbluebeard slayer\u201d of his second and\nthird wives.\nKolb was cross examined concern\ning testimony he delivered when he\ntook the witness stand in his own de\nfense in his trial in Hancock county\ncircuit court on a charge of murder\ning his third wife, Mrs. Edna Dagler\nKolb.\nThe Rush county man sobbed as he\nrelated details of the deaths of his\nsecond and third wives and vigorously\ndenied charges that he poisoned them\nto obtain Insurance policies carried on\ntheir lives.\nKolb said that he tried to poison\nhimself because he was sick and wor\nried by the accusations that he had\nmurdered his wives.\nWOMAN WHO SAW\nREPORTER KILLED\nHELD BY POLICE\nSt. Louis Reporter Siays\nCapone Knows Slayer\nof Newspaper Man.\nBy Fnltrd Press:\nCHICAGO, July 18.\u2014Somewhere in\nChicago Friday night was a woman\nwho witnessed the assassination of\nAlfred \"Jake\u201d Lingle, Chicago Tribune\nreporter.\nShe was on the verge of a nervous\ncreakdown and in hiding, fearful that\ngangster bullets might find her should\n>he appear in public.\nState's Attorney John A. Swanson\n>aid, however, that she had promised\n:o testify and that his detectives\nMeanwhile were guarding her.\nKey Witness\n\u201cShe saw the killer shoot Lingle In\n;he subway under Michigan boulevard\n~ive weeks ago,\u201d said Johnson. \"We re\ngard her as the key to the killing. It\n,s the first tangible progress we have\nnaae toward solving the mystery.\u201d\nSwanson refused to say more about\n;he witness, to name her or say where\n\u2022he might be found on the ground\n;hat to do so would endanger her life\nis well as the progress of the Lingle\nnurder investigation.\nPublication of a copyright article by\nHarry T. Brundidge, St. Louis Star\n\u2022eporter, concerning an interview in\nMiami, Fla., with \"Scarface Al\u201d Ca\npone was another sensational devel\nAnf a^ rt /Intr\nBundidge, who charged recently\nhat many Chicago newspaper report\n:rs are allied with the underworld and\n?:ho has promised to substantiate his\n:harges before a grand jury here\nruesday, quoted Capone as saying the\nChicago police know who killed Lingle.\n\u201cLay Off Chicago\u201d\n\u201cThe big beer and bullet baron put\niis left arm around my shoulders.\u201d\n3rundidge continued \u201cand with typi\n:al Latin affection, squeezed me and\n:aid: \u2018Listen Harry, I like your face.\nLet me give you a hot tip. Lay off\nChicago and the money-hungry re\nnters.\n\u201cYou're right and because you\u2019re\nright, you\u2019re wrong. You can\u2019t buck\nt, not even with the backing of your\nnewspaper, because ijt's too big a\nproposition.\n\"No matter what dope you have to\ngive the grand jury the boys will\nprove you\u2019re a liar and a faker!\u201d\nBrundidge added that Capone said\nhere was a number of newspapermen\nm his payroll and that Lingle got in\nfinancial trouble because of his love\nlor gambling on horse races.\nIt was Lingle\u2019s loss of money and\nlis insistance that the underworld in\n:rease his share of the profits, ac\n:ording to all theories, which led ul\n;imately to his assassination.\nbrueningIolds\nGERMANY\u2019S FATE\nNew Dictator Chosen As\nReichstag Is Dis\nv solved.\nBy ERIC KEYSER\nUnited Press Staff Correspondent\nBERLIN July 18.\u2014The financial\nate of Germany, which faces a de\nicit in the current budget of approxi\nnately $115,000,000, was turned over\n,oday to a dictatorship headed by Dr.\n3einrich Bruening, young economist\nind chancellor of the Reich.\nPresident Paul Von Hindenburg\nlissolved the Reichstag by decree to\niay after members by a vote of 236 to\n!21 rescinded the dictatorial financial\njowers previously bestowed on Bruen\nng by the president.\nThe crowded Reichstag was tense\nvhen after it had defied the threat\n>f article 48 of the constitution which\nirovides for a dictatorship, the schol\nirly looking chancellor faced it, pale\nind nervous and read the decree of\nlissolution in a trembling voice.\nThe communist, defiant as always,\nnarched out shouting the \u201cInterna\nionale\u201d song. Their ranks were de\nleted by 10 members, in hiding now\nhat dissolution of the Reichstag has\n\u2022emoved their parliamentary im\nnunity and made them liable to\nirosecution for past treasonable acts.\nThe dictatorship now in effect is\niot like the absolute rule enforced\nn all governmental matters by Mus\nolini and other European dictators.\nIt undoubtedly will not be used to\nmy extent except to solve the finan\n:ial crisis.\nSince the Reichstag was dissolved\ndthout enacting the 1930 budget and\nifter it had rendered the previous\nax decrees invalid by its vote, the\ngovernment will fix revenues and ex\njenditures by decree. The program\nwill entail a program of rigid reduc\nion of expenditures and heavy new\naxes.\nToday\u2019s Index\nPage Section\nEditorials a 6 ,1\nSociety. 8 1\n\"Girl Unafraid\u201d 1 2\nRadio.' 2 2\nAmusements 2 2\nSports ...4-5-6 2\nState 15 2\nMishawaka 12 .2\nComic Page .t.; 13 2\nMarkets. 14 2\nClassified Ads 16-17 2\n.r 4","height":"32624","width":"24004"}}
